'''塞雷尔人'''（{{lang-fr|Sérères}}；{{lang-en|Serer people}}），[[西非|西非]]民族，依人口计算是[[塞内加尔|塞内加尔]]的第三大民族，占塞内加尔人口的15%<ref>[https://www.cia.gov/the-world-factbook/countries/senegal/ Senegal] {{Wayback|url=https://www.cia.gov/the-world-factbook/countries/senegal/ |date=20210204143936 }}, CIA Factsheet</ref>。在[[冈比亚|冈比亚]]北部和[[毛里塔尼亚|毛里塔尼亚]]南部也有分布<ref>[http://www.ethnologue.com/show_country.asp?name=GM] {{Wayback|url=http://www.ethnologue.com/show_country.asp?name=GM |date=20121004134442 }} Ethnologue.com</ref>。

塞雷尔人的祖先来自塞内加尔和毛里塔尼亚边界的[[塞内加尔河|塞内加尔河]]河谷地区，在11世纪至12世纪南迁，15世纪至16世纪因战乱和宗教压力再度南迁<ref name="Galvan">Galvan, Dennis Charles, ''The State Must Be Our Master of Fire: How Peasants Craft Culturally Sustainable Development in Senegal'' Berkeley, University of California Press, 2004 p. 51</ref><ref name=berg63/><ref name="Villalón2006p54">{{cite book|author=Leonardo A. Villalón|title=Islamic Society and State Power in Senegal: Disciples and Citizens in Fatick|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xFC1KUbXJ6gC&pg=PA54|year=2006|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-03232-2|pages=54–55|access-date=2021-02-08|archive-date=2021-03-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210303163513/https://books.google.com/books?id=xFC1KUbXJ6gC&pg=PA54|dead-url=no}}, Quote: "Serer oral tradition recounts the group's origins in the Senegal River valley, where it was part of, or closely related to, the same group as the ancestors of today's Tukulor."</ref>。传统上从事定居农业，精于农耕和[[移牧|移牧式]]畜牧<ref name=berg63>{{cite book|author1=Elizabeth Berg|author2=Ruth Wan|author3=Ruth Lau|title=Senegal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2hjbZ0o-GloC&pg=PA63|year=2009|publisher=Marshall Cavendish|isbn=978-0-7614-4481-7|page=63|access-date=2021-02-08|archive-date=2021-03-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210303163748/https://books.google.com/books?id=2hjbZ0o-GloC&pg=PA63|dead-url=no}}</ref><ref>Natural Resources Research, [[联合国教育、科学及文化组织|UNESCO]], ''Natural resources research, Volume 16'', Unesco (1979), p. 265</ref>。

塞雷尔人在历史上长期实行[[母系制度|母系制度]]，抗拒伊斯兰教传播，在19世纪起先后和西非的伊斯兰教圣战者和法国殖民者对抗<ref name=olson516/><ref name="Diop">Pierret, Paul, "Dictionnaire d'archéologie égyptienne", Imprimerie nationale 1875, p. 198-199 [in] Diop, Cheikh Anta, "Precolonial Black Africa", (trans: Harold Salemson), Chicago Review Press, 1988, p. 65</ref><ref name="Martin A. Klein 1968">See Godfrey Mwakikagile in Martin A. Klein. ''Islam and Imperialism in Senegal Sine-Saloum, 1847–1914'', Edinburgh at the University Press (1968)</ref>。然而到20世纪，绝大部分塞雷尔人都皈依伊斯兰教，以[[苏菲主义|苏菲派]]为主<ref name="Villalón2006p71">{{cite book|author=Leonardo A. Villalón|title=Islamic Society and State Power in Senegal: Disciples and Citizens in Fatick|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xFC1KUbXJ6gC&pg=PA73|year=2006|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-03232-2|pages=71–74|access-date=2021-02-08|archive-date=2020-10-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201025214944/https://books.google.com/books?id=xFC1KUbXJ6gC&pg=PA73|dead-url=no}}</ref><ref name=olson516>{{cite book|author=James Stuart Olson|title=The Peoples of Africa: An Ethnohistorical Dictionary|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MdaAdBC-_S4C&pg=PA516|year=1996|publisher=Greenwood|isbn=978-0-313-27918-8|page=516|access-date=2021-02-08|archive-date=2020-08-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200804133831/https://books.google.com/books?id=MdaAdBC-_S4C|dead-url=no}}</ref>。和塞内加尔的其他民族相似，塞雷尔人的社会也存在着基于氏族内婚和奴隶制度的阶级分野<ref name="Resnick2013p165">{{cite book|author=Danielle Resnick|title=Urban Poverty and Party Populism in African Democracies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EWfLAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA165 |year=2013|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-107-65723-6|page=165}}, Quote:"One reason for the low salience of ethnic identity is because, like some other West African societies, many ethnic groups in Senegal are structured by caste. For example, the Wolof, '''Serer''', and Pulaar-speaking Toucouleur are all caste societies."</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Martin A. Klein|title=Islam and Imperialism in Senegal: Sine-Saloum, 1847–1914|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JPSrAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA7|year=1968|publisher=Stanford University Press|isbn=978-0-8047-0621-6|pages=7–11}}</ref><ref name=tamari221>{{cite journal|author=Tal Tamari| year= 1991|title= The Development of Caste Systems in West Africa| journal= The Journal of African History| volume= 32| number= 2| pages= 221–250|publisher= Cambridge University Press| jstor= 182616| doi=10.1017/s0021853700025718}}, '''Quote:''' "[Castes] are found among the Soninke, the various Manding-speaking populations, the Wolof, Tukulor, Senufo, Minianka, Dogon, Songhay, and most Fulani, Moorish and Tuareg populations, (...) They are also found among (...) and Serer groups."</ref>。

